\section*{Types of Numbers}

Python has various \textit{"types"} of numbers (numeric literals). We'll mainly focus on integers and floating-point numbers.\\\

Integers are just whole numbers, positive or negative.
\\\

For example: 9 and -2 are examples of integers.\\\


Floating-point numbers in Python have a decimal point in them or use an exponential (\textit{e}) to define the number. \\

For example, 0.7 and -2.09 are examples of floating-point numbers. \(4e^3\) (4 times 10 to the power of 3) is also an example of a floating-point number in Python.\\


Here is a table of the two main types we will spend most of our time working with, along with some examples:\\

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline
\textbf{Examples} & \textbf{Number "Type"} \\
\hline
1, 2, -5, 1000 & Integers \\
\hline
1.2, -0.5, \(-7e^2\) & Floating-point numbers \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}\\\


\\\

\begin{document}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|}
